gomodel:SYNGO_5099  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Figure 1: Neurl1 is expressed in the adult mouse forebrain and is localized in dendrites and at post-synaptic sites in hippocampal neurons.\n\nFigure 3: Overexpression of Neurl1 in the adult hippocampus results in enhanced learning and memory and increased synaptic plasticity.\n\nFigure 4: Neurl1 overexpression in the hippocampus increases the number of spines and functional synapses and the number of AMPAR subunits GluA1 and GluA2.\n\nFigure 5: Neurl1 interacts with and ubiquitinates CPEB3.\n\nFigure 6: Neurl1-dependent ubiquitination and ubiquitin modulate the activity of CPEB3 and increase CPEB3-dependent polyadenylation and translation of GluA1 and GluA2 leading to an increase of their protein levels.\n\nFigure 7: Neurl1 and ubiquitin increase spine number by modulating the translational activity of CPEB3.\n\nAuthors summarize:\n\"Taken together, our data suggest that the ability of Neurl1 to ubiquitinate CPEB3 is a limiting factor and facilitates hippocampal synaptic plasticity and hippocampal-dependent memory by modulating CPEB3 translational activity through ubiquitination with consequent induction of an increase of GluA1 and GluA2 protein levels and the formation of new spines.\". Experimental description: suppl. M&M: \"Immunohistochemistry - Three-month-old mice were anesthetized and perfused ...\"\n\nantibody:\n\"Affinity-purified rabbit polyclonal sera directed against an N-terminal peptide sequence of mouse Neurl1 (amino acids 27-42; peptide generated by Global Peptides), were produced by Covance.\"\n\nthe specificity of the affinity purified anti-Neurl1 antibody was validated in Figure S1." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-4973-5732" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2023-02-24" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_5099" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

